<dl id="n10093f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10093f">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10093f"> 93(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> remittance (man) <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n10093f"><li>FW 428.25 </li><li><a href="../../flex/pD/lexpD.htm#n10093f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/pD/l39pD.htm#n10093f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n10093f">MS BL 47482b-44v</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:090 <a name="pA3d" href="../../ff/fdra/pda.htm#pD3d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/p/pD3d.htm#n10093f">Draft: III&sect;1D.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">il ne faut pourtant pas comparer ce message &agrave; ce qu&apos;on appelle de nos jours une lettre mise &agrave; la Poste. Il est probable que la Poste transporta quelque envoy&eacute; du Parlement, porteur de la lettre, et que cet envoy&eacute; <mark>la remit avec un peu plus de solennit&eacute; que ne le ferait un facteur</mark> de notre temps. <font color="green">[However, one should not compare this message with the one that we now call &lsquo;a letter sent through the post&rsquo;. It is likely that the Post transported some Parliamentary envoy, carrying a letter, and that this envoy remitted it with a little more solemnity than a contemporary postman.]</font> <small> Arthur de Rothschild, <a name="ARHD" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ARHD"><cite title="source">Histoire de la poste</cite></a> (1876) 141</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: A remittance man is an emigrant supported by money from home. (OED) </mm> </dd></dl>
